'''Immanent evaluation''' is a [[philosophical]] concept used by [[Gilles Deleuze]] in his essay "Qu'est-ce qu'un dispositif ?" (1989), where it is seen as the opposite of [[transcendence (philosophy)|transcendent]] [[judgment (philosophy)|judgment]].

Deleuze writes about [[Michel Foucault]]: "Foucault ... makes allusion to 'aesthetic' criteria, which are understood as criteria for life and replace on each occasion the claims of transcendental {{sic}} judgement [''jugement transcendant''] with an immanent evaluation [''évaluation immanente'']".<ref>Gilles Deleuze. 1992. "What Is a dispositif?" In: ''Michel Foucault: Philosopher''. Ed. T. J. Armstrong. Hartfordshire: Harvester Wheatsheft, 159–168, esp. 163; original: "Qu'est-ce qu'un dispositif ?" in Association pour le Centre Michel Foucault, ''Michel Foucault, philosophe'', Seuil, 1989, p. 189.</ref>

